00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:30.560
My job is to take these ideas that exist in
my head and tell them how to make them come

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:32.810
to life.

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:37.310
We do that through a process we call protosepting.

00:04:37.310 --> 00:04:42.660
In the process of protosepting, I found myself
side by side with my food technologists and

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:48.880
chef colleagues, 15 years ago when I started
in this business, not knowing what the hell

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:50.440
was happening.

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:57.630
Why would I taste something that was as simple
as a tortilla chip and say, "Yeah, I like

00:04:57.630 --> 00:05:02.410
B better than A and C." And they would taste
that same tortilla chip and they would get

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:07.030
so much more sensory output from it.

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:09.560
So I set out looking for a book.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:13.620
I was looking for this book that would explain
to me what was happening when I put food in

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:16.540
my mouth and chew and swallow.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:18.990
I looked and I looked and I looked.

00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:21.030
That book did not exist.

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:27.490
So I ended up having to learn through a painful
process of experience, what was happening

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:30.550
as I was tasting in the lab.

00:05:30.550 --> 00:05:37.330
About five years ago, I decided that that
book that I'd wanted 15 years ago, I was going

00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:38.330
to write it.

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:44.160
I set out on a process of doing some research
into this field of sensory science.

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:45.970
That's the result.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:49.210
My book is the result of that experience.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:52.259
The book is called Taste What You're Missing.

00:05:52.259 --> 00:05:56.130
It's basically about how we taste.

00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:57.790
There are three sections to the book.

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:03.400
The first one is about the five senses, because
we don't really think about the fact that

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:07.069
food and eating is a multisensory experience.

00:06:07.069 --> 00:06:10.350
We say it's about taste: I like the taste
of something.

00:06:10.350 --> 00:06:14.811
Well, actually, if you like the taste of chocolate,
for example, you like the way it looks, you

00:06:14.811 --> 00:06:19.591
like the way it feels, you like the way it
sounds, you like the way it smells, and you

00:06:19.591 --> 00:06:21.979
like the way it tastes.

00:06:21.979 --> 00:06:26.930
The second part of the book then goes into
great depth about our sense of taste.

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:33.910
There are only five things that human beings
can detect using only that one sense: sweet,

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:36.270
sour, bitter, salt, and umami.

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:42.120
If it's not one of those five things, you're
not using your sense of taste alone.

00:06:42.120 --> 00:06:50.389
So chocolate that I mentioned, the taste of
chocolate is sweet and bitter, perhaps a little

00:06:50.389 --> 00:06:52.660
bit sour.

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:53.660
That's it.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:55.949
It's the only tastes you get from chocolate.

00:06:55.949 --> 00:07:00.690
Everything else that's happening that makes
chocolate so wonderful: the melting quality

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:05.680
of chocolate, which just happens to melt at
human body temperature, precisely at human

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:08.490
body temperature, that's the texture of it.

00:07:08.490 --> 00:07:14.340
The aromas of the roasty, toasty, beany notes,
that's the smell of it.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:17.210
And of course, it makes a sound when we snap
it.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:22.710
Visually, it should look beautifully dark
and glossy and chocolatey.

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:27.690
The end of the book brings all these things
together: your five senses, the five basic

00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:32.241
tastes, and then layers onto it other stuff
that impacts the way you experience food:

00:07:32.241 --> 00:07:38.889
of course your culture, your personality,
your experience, and your brain.

00:07:38.889 --> 00:07:40.120
Okay.

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:43.789
We're going to start now, go through each
one of the five senses.

00:07:43.789 --> 00:07:49.930
I'm going to start with-- I told you, there
are only five things that we can taste.

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:55.229
I'm going to tell you a little bit of a story
about how I came to appreciate my sense of

00:07:55.229 --> 00:07:56.229
taste.

00:07:56.229 --> 00:08:01.440
Now you have to go back with me to Foster
City, in the lab, a couple of years ago.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:07.060
We had been hired by this company to develop
new appetizers for the restaurant industry.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:10.620
This is my job, to think up new appetizers
that haven't been done.

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:12.470
I new right away what I wanted to do.

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:13.910
I grew up in Baltimore.

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:15.970
My dad used to grow tomatoes.

00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:21.870
I wanted to do fried green tomatoes, which
he used to make every Sunday for breakfast.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:26.190
So I enlisted one of my chefs to start prototyping
this.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:31.250
It turns out, because we were going to sell
these in huge quantities, frozen, that sliced

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:33.319
green tomatoes were too flimsy and too wet.

00:08:33.319 --> 00:08:34.570
They weren't going to work.

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:37.919
So she said, "What if we do fried green cherry
tomatoes?"

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.130
"All right, let's try that."

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:43.339
Then my chef came back to me and said, "You
know what, we can't find the green ones.

00:08:43.339 --> 00:08:45.450
I can only get red ones to start prototyping.

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:47.070
Is that okay?"

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:52.800
So I said, "All right: fried red cherry tomatoes.

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:54.560
Let's try it."

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:58.420
We decided we would put a cornmeal crust on
it.

00:08:58.420 --> 00:09:03.230
I get a page one day, and it says, "Barb,
please come to the lab.

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:05.350
The prototype is ready for you to taste."

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:08.050
Now this is my favorite part of my job.

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:12.990
This is when the idea that exists up here
comes to life and I get to taste it.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:14.930
I walk into the lab.

00:09:14.930 --> 00:09:20.760
My chef is dropping these beautiful cornmeal-crusted
cherry tomatoes into the fryer.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:23.430
They're bubbling around in the fryer, and
they're golden-coated.

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:28.480
I know this is going to be a great idea.

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:35.310
Just as she pulls the basket out of the fryer,
shakes it, I reach my hand into the basket

00:09:35.310 --> 00:09:41.870
to grab one of these lovely prototypes and
put it in my mouth, I hear her start to scream.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:54.050
[screams] [laughter] That 375 degree cherry
tomato, I spit it out across the room, along

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:55.970
with the roof of my mouth.

00:09:55.970 --> 00:10:00.300
[laughter] My entire tongue was traumatized.

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:04.110
Burned off a lot of taste buds.

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:07.210
I thought, "There goes my tasting career.

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:09.330
I'm a professional taster who can't taste.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.290
What am I going to do?"

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:20.192
Well, lucky for me, taste is such an important
sense that these taste buds that I burned

00:10:20.192 --> 00:10:23.680
off would regenerate in 10 to 14 days.

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:29.390
In fact, they're constantly regenerating on
your tongue, every 10 to 14 days.

00:10:29.390 --> 00:10:31.600
Taste is a contact sense.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:32.600
Think about it.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:36.430
Food has to be in contact with your tongue
for you to be able to experience it.

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:41.839
That's different than the sense of smell or
hearing or sight, which can happen from a

00:10:41.839 --> 00:10:42.839
distance.

00:10:42.839 --> 00:10:44.930
But taste has to be a contact sense.

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:49.760
So it's important that these taste buds on
your tongue work.

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:54.850
We also found out very recently that there
are taste buds in your gut.

00:10:54.850 --> 00:11:01.000
Now, not just food sensor receptors down there,
but actual taste buds.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.649
Of course, this makes good intuitive sense
when you think about it, because your stomach

00:11:05.649 --> 00:11:08.360
needs to know what to do with the food you've
just eaten.

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:10.920
It needs to tell your body how to start digesting
it.

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:15.070
So it would make sense that it says, "Oh,
there's some sweetness here" or "There's some

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:16.070
protein here."

00:11:16.070 --> 00:11:22.450
Now I'm going to talk a little bit about this
very important sense.

00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:27.880
There are three things that determine your
taster type.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:32.230
Your taster type is how you experience the
taste world.

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:36.779
Each one of us experiences the taste world
very, very, very differently.

00:11:36.779 --> 00:11:40.420
But remember, I'm only talking about this
one sense.

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:42.200
We'll get to the other senses later.

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:47.510
