I think everybody on our panel is a taster,
which means that they, like the majority of

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:11.089
the population, fall in this middle group
of people that have a good number of taste

00:15:11.089 --> 00:15:14.470
buds on their tongue.

00:15:14.470 --> 00:15:19.730
The last thing that indicates your taster
type is your personal history.

00:15:19.730 --> 00:15:24.710
Now that I've told you about my trauma with
the tomato, there are other things you can

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:27.120
do that traumatize your mouth.

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:32.350
There are surgeries or viruses that you might
have had that can damage your taste nerves.

00:15:32.350 --> 00:15:35.330
If you've had your wisdom teeth pulled, for
example.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:39.269
When you have your wisdom teeth pulled, it
happens very close to one of the taste nerves,

00:15:39.269 --> 00:15:41.120
the chorda tympani nerve.

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:47.070
That, if you snip it, can take out taste in
the front part of your mouth.

00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:48.990
If you've had ear infections as a kid.

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:55.850
If you had those recurrent ear infections,
that may have damaged your taste nerve.

00:15:55.850 --> 00:16:00.880
There's a lot of things that can go into your
personal experience that are going to layer

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:05.870
on top of your genetics and your anatomy.

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:07.560
Okay.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:11.200
So now we're going to move onto more pleasant
tastes.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:14.940
We're going to start with sweet.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:20.490
Taste-- Let me just say for a minute, the
sense of taste is so important that we wire

00:16:20.490 --> 00:16:25.440
it so that it's constantly regenerating.

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:28.670
We call taste the deciding sense.

00:16:28.670 --> 00:16:33.259
You put a food in your mouth, you have to
make a decision whether or not you're going

00:16:33.259 --> 00:16:34.290
to swallow it.

00:16:34.290 --> 00:16:36.600
You swallow it, you get nourished.

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:39.400
You spit it out, you don't.

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:42.720
You swallow something that's poisonous, you
can kill yourself.

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:44.350
You spit it out, you don't.

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:46.509
Taste is about making decisions.

00:16:46.509 --> 00:16:49.470
Smell, on the other hand, is about enjoyment.

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:52.839
We're going to talk about smell in a minute.

00:16:52.839 --> 00:16:54.970
But, back to taste.

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:55.970
Sweet.

00:16:55.970 --> 00:16:59.330
We know that babies are born loving sweet.

00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:02.670
They come out of the womb, you can put a little
sugar in their mouth, and they will light

00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:03.670
up.

00:17:03.670 --> 00:17:04.670
Love sugar.

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:06.300
Why are we wired this way?

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:07.699
Why do we love sugar?

00:17:07.699 --> 00:17:09.150
Why do we love the taste "sweet?"

00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:11.010
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Energy?

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:12.260
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Absolutely.

00:17:12.260 --> 00:17:16.850
It's a flashing neon sign for calories.

00:17:16.850 --> 00:17:18.540
Sweet equals calories.

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:25.819
If, God forbid, there was a little baby crawling
around back when we were cavemen, looking

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:30.510
for food in any way, shape, or form we could
get it, you find something sweet, a little

00:17:30.510 --> 00:17:32.990
baby finds something sweet, they can nourish
themselves.

00:17:32.990 --> 00:17:36.980
So we're wired from the get-go to like sweet.

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:38.760
Sour.

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:41.320
This one's a little bit more complicated.

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:44.679
Why do you think we can detect sour?

00:17:44.679 --> 00:17:47.520
What is it that sour communicates to us?

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:49.059
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Vitamin C.

00:17:49.059 --> 00:17:50.210
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Vitamin C?

00:17:50.210 --> 00:17:51.670
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Not ripe.

00:17:51.670 --> 00:17:52.670
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Not ripe!

00:17:52.670 --> 00:17:53.670
Yes.

00:17:53.670 --> 00:17:54.670
Exactly.

00:17:54.670 --> 00:17:55.910
You're the first person I've ever gotten that
from.

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:58.100
I've given this to hundreds and hundreds of
people.

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:00.220
That's exactly right.

00:18:00.220 --> 00:18:05.130
If you take an apple off the tree, you take
a bite of it and it's too sour, might give

00:18:05.130 --> 00:18:06.190
you stomachache.

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:11.990
Well, not only that, but at the point where
that sweetness and the sourness in the apple

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:16.540
are at that perfect balance where you take
the bite and you go, "That's a good apple",

00:18:16.540 --> 00:18:20.170
that is when the apple is at its nutritional
peak.

00:18:20.170 --> 00:18:22.419
It has the highest level of micro-nutrients.

00:18:22.419 --> 00:18:26.290
After that point, it starts to decline.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:28.970
It's an indicator of ripeness, exactly right.

00:18:28.970 --> 00:18:30.570
What else does sour do?

00:18:30.570 --> 00:18:33.360
What does it tell us?

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:35.530
When the milk goes bad, it goes what?

00:18:35.530 --> 00:18:36.530
&gt;&gt;audience: Sour.

00:18:36.530 --> 00:18:37.530
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Sour.

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:38.530
Right.

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:39.600
So it's a spoilage mechanism.

00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:41.100
It's a spoilage indicator.

00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:46.419
You taste something that's not supposed to
be sour and it's sour, you don't eat it.

00:18:46.419 --> 00:18:48.169
Protective.

00:18:48.169 --> 00:18:49.919
Bitter.

00:18:49.919 --> 00:18:51.300
Now let's talk about bitter.

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:54.580
My people that are sitting up here just experienced
bitter.

00:18:54.580 --> 00:18:57.240
What is it about bitter that we need to know?

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:59.950
Why do we innately reject bitter?

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:01.860
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Poisonous.

00:19:01.860 --> 00:19:03.130
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Poisonous.

00:19:03.130 --> 00:19:04.130
Exactly.

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:07.200
Most poisons taste bitter.

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:14.520
What's even more interesting, though, is most
bitter things are poisonous in the right quantity.

00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:16.920
So you say, "What a second, I drink coffee,
that's bitter.

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:17.920
I drink red wine, that's bitter.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:20.360
They're not poisonous."

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:27.289
They're not, but the compounds in those foods
that make them bitter, if you ate enough of

00:19:27.289 --> 00:19:29.179
those compounds, you could die.

00:19:29.179 --> 00:19:34.830
Of course, you'd have to eat a lot of coffee,
you have a drink a lot of red wine.

00:19:34.830 --> 00:19:38.039
So we generally don't ingest enough.

00:19:38.039 --> 00:19:46.440
But what bitter indicates is that there's
something happening pharmaceutically or there's

00:19:46.440 --> 00:19:49.429
some medicinal thing going on.

00:19:49.429 --> 00:19:55.360
There are bioactives that are good for us
in certain doses, maybe not so good for us

00:19:55.360 --> 00:19:57.840
in megadoses.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:03.100
Most medicines what taste bitter, bitter medicine.

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:09.169
That's because the compounds in there that
are bioactive are tasting bitter.

00:20:09.169 --> 00:20:11.980
&gt;&gt;Male #4: What about Brussels sprouts?

00:20:11.980 --> 00:20:12.980
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: What about Brussels sprouts?

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:13.980
Pardon?

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:14.980
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Why are they bitter?

00:20:14.980 --> 00:20:17.960
I haven't heard of anyone overdosing and dying--

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:23.429
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: [laughs] You'd have to eat a lot
of Brussels sprouts in order to overdose on

00:20:23.429 --> 00:20:24.429
Brussels sprouts.

00:20:24.429 --> 00:20:27.040
In fact, so much so that I don't think you
could physically get there.

00:20:27.040 --> 00:20:30.030
It would be so uncomfortable for you and everyone
around you.

00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:32.380
[laughter] So you just don't want to go there.

00:20:32.380 --> 00:20:36.590
[laughs] The compound in it, though, if you
extracted that, that's what I'm talking about.

00:20:36.590 --> 00:20:37.590
Yes?

00:20:37.590 --> 00:20:41.370
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Is it the same with spinach or
green leafy vegetables?

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:42.370
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes.

00:20:42.370 --> 00:20:43.370
Most green, leafy vegetables, yeah.

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:48.270
All the things in food that make them healthy
and good for you are bitter.

00:20:48.270 --> 00:20:53.600
I know this because we do a lot of work at
Mattson in fortifying foods with things like

00:20:53.600 --> 00:20:57.110
antioxidants and polyphenols and flavonols.

00:20:57.110 --> 00:20:59.919
All of those things taste extremely bitter.

00:20:59.919 --> 00:21:01.299
Salt.

00:21:01.299 --> 00:21:08.270
When we're born, we can't taste salt.

00:21:08.270 --> 00:21:12.039
Come out of the womb, and we do not have the
mature salt receptor.

00:21:12.039 --> 00:21:18.080
Now this terrible story about how we found
out that this is the case is that in Australia,

00:21:18.080 --> 00:21:20.650
they used to mix baby formula.

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:23.929
So they'd mix the sugar with the baby formula
and feed it to the kids.

00:21:23.929 --> 00:21:30.520
Well, at this hospital, someone mistakenly
sugar with the formula and fed it to the babies.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:34.880
They drank it like they just drank their normal
formula.

00:21:34.880 --> 00:21:35.880
Didn't reject it.

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:36.980
You know when babies don't want something.

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:38.990
They will let you know that they don't want
it.

00:21:38.990 --> 00:21:41.159
No response whatsoever from the babies.

00:21:41.159 --> 00:21:47.429
The babies drank this incredibly salty formula,
and some of them died from salt poisoning.

00:21:47.429 --> 00:21:50.350
Horrible, horrible story.

00:21:50.350 --> 00:21:53.640
But we learned that we don't have mature salt
receptors.

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:56.260
But then, at a certain age, they kick in.

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:58.070
And boy, do they kick in.

00:21:58.070 --> 00:22:02.020
We love our salt.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:04.640
Salt obviously provides sodium.

00:22:04.640 --> 00:22:10.549
We need sodium for our cell function.

00:22:10.549 --> 00:22:15.590
We also need things like calcium, which we
don't really crave in the same way.

00:22:15.590 --> 00:22:19.990
We need a lot of other micronutrients that
we don't crave in the same way.

00:22:19.990 --> 00:22:22.100
Why do we crave salt this way?

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:24.059
The way that we do?

00:22:24.059 --> 00:22:30.299
The reason is we don't have a way to store
sodium in our bodies.

00:22:30.299 --> 00:22:33.140
You can take in calcium in your diet, you
can store it in your bones, you can store

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:34.170
it in your teeth.

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:39.180
You take in some sodium, and you can store
it through water retention, but eventually,

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:40.180
you'll lose it.

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:46.140
You'll lose it through crying and sweating
and other excretion from your body.

00:22:46.140 --> 00:22:49.280
You constantly need to replenish your body
with sodium.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:56.540
Of course, that was a hangover from old times
when we used to have to really, really seek

00:22:56.540 --> 00:22:57.540
out sodium.

00:22:57.540 --> 00:23:01.090
Today, we have easy access to sodium, and
we don't sweat as much, I guess we don't cry

00:23:01.090 --> 00:23:03.919
as much, so we don't lose as much.

00:23:03.919 --> 00:23:07.860
Now we're taking in more sodium than we need.

00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:13.960
You have-- One of your clear cups is labeled
"S", and this is salt.

00:23:13.960 --> 00:23:18.040
I want you to just take a sip of the salt
water and remind yourselves what salt water

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:19.040
tastes like.

00:23:19.040 --> 00:23:21.350
This is going to be important in a minute.

00:23:21.350 --> 00:23:26.590
I find that most people understand four of
the five basic tastes: the sweet, the salt,

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:28.470
the bitter, the sour.

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:34.590
But we're going to get to the last one, umami,
in a minute, which people are a little confused

00:23:34.590 --> 00:23:35.590
about.

00:23:35.590 --> 00:23:36.590
Okay.

00:23:36.590 --> 00:23:37.590
Salt water.

00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:38.590
What does it taste like?

00:23:38.590 --> 00:23:39.590
Go ahead, take a sip.

00:23:39.590 --> 00:23:40.590
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Drink it?

00:23:40.590 --> 00:23:43.370
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: No, no, no, you don't have to--
[laughs] Just take enough that you can taste

00:23:43.370 --> 00:23:44.370
the salt in it.

00:23:44.370 --> 00:23:45.370
Can you taste it?

00:23:45.370 --> 00:23:46.370
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Yes.

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:47.370
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes.

00:23:47.370 --> 00:23:48.370
Okay.

00:23:48.370 --> 00:23:49.419
That's calibrating your palate.

00:23:49.419 --> 00:23:53.210
Calibrating your palate at a certain sodium
level.

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:54.210
Now we're going to move on.

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:55.210
Ah, no, we're not.

00:23:55.210 --> 00:23:58.320
I wanted to tell you one more thing about
salt, which is-- and I write about this in

00:23:58.320 --> 00:23:59.320
the book.

00:23:59.320 --> 00:24:01.029
I have a chapter on each of the basic tastes.

00:24:01.029 --> 00:24:04.230
I call salt the superhero of taste.

00:24:04.230 --> 00:24:06.429
It is amazing what salt can do.

00:24:06.429 --> 00:24:08.710
I mean, I don't really need to tell people
salt's amazing.

00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:10.039
We know it's really good.

00:24:10.039 --> 00:24:12.110
But the way it works is so cool.

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:17.170
The first thing that salt does is that when
you salt a food, take a tomato, for example,

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:20.539
you upset the cellular balance of that tomato.

00:24:20.539 --> 00:24:27.550
What happens is it forces these aroma compounds
out of the cells into the air.

00:24:27.550 --> 00:24:33.809
By salting food, you are giving it more aroma,
which gives it more flavor.

00:24:33.809 --> 00:24:39.640
Salt not just adds saltiness, it really does
give food more flavor.

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:44.450
The other thing that salt does is-- I call
it the superhero because it suppresses the

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:48.260
bad guys and it lets the good guys run free.

00:24:48.260 --> 00:24:51.580
The bad guys of taste being bitter, of course.

00:24:51.580 --> 00:24:56.940
A little bit of salt suppresses the bitterness
of something and allows the sweetness, the

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.200
good taste, to come forward.

00:24:59.200 --> 00:25:01.260
I've got a little wedge of grapefruit there.

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:08.940
I recommend you go home and take a grapefruit,
cut it into wedges, put some salt in a bowl,

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:11.940
and sprinkle salt on half of the wedges.

00:25:11.940 --> 00:25:16.799
Take the other half of the wedges, take that
same bowl of salt, add a little touch-- same

00:25:16.799 --> 00:25:21.050
bowl of sugar, add a little touch of salt,
and then sprinkle that.

00:25:21.050 --> 00:25:25.780
Taste the one with the sugar on it, and it
will taste nice and sweet with a balance of

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:30.230
the salt and the bitter that's naturally present
in the grapefruit.

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:33.669
Then you go to the one that has a little bit
of salt added to the sugar.

00:25:33.669 --> 00:25:40.970
It will taste sweeter because the salt is
suppressing the bitterness and letting the

00:25:40.970 --> 00:25:42.919
sweetness come forward.

00:25:42.919 --> 00:25:45.990
So salt is really the superhero of taste.

00:25:45.990 --> 00:25:49.380
&gt;&gt;Female: Quick question.

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:53.722
When it comes to cooking, then, does that
mean you should only salt at the very end?

00:25:53.722 --> 00:25:54.722
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: That's a good question.

00:25:54.722 --> 00:25:58.390
The question was: should you salt food only
at the end?

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:02.490
Salting the food in the middle of the cooking
process will help marry the flavors.

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:08.100
So yes, I would suggest salting during the
cooking process, but saving some of the salt

00:26:08.100 --> 00:26:10.929
so that you do have the ability to do it at
the table.

00:26:10.929 --> 00:26:14.180
So I would never add all the salt that you
want in the recipe.

00:26:14.180 --> 00:26:18.390
You want to leave a little bit of it out so
you can add it at the very last minute.

00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:23.000
Any of those volatile aroma compounds that
are left will be forced out and into the air.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:26.179
That will give you more aroma, the food more
aroma.

00:26:26.179 --> 00:26:27.179
Okay.

00:26:27.179 --> 00:26:29.250
Now the fifth basic taste, which is umami.

00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:36.640
Umami, of course, is a Japanese word for which
we don't have a really good translation.

00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:41.010
We call it brothy or meaty or savory.

00:26:41.010 --> 00:26:46.159
We don't have a really good way of describing
this taste, so we borrow the Japanese word.

00:26:46.159 --> 00:26:49.409
I'm going to ask our panelists here.

00:26:49.409 --> 00:26:51.400
Take the cup with the "U" on it.

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:53.179
That is our umami water.

00:26:53.179 --> 00:26:58.050
I've matched the sodium level in the umami
water so I'm going to ask you guys to describe

00:26:58.050 --> 00:26:59.050
it.

00:26:59.050 --> 00:27:00.050
What does it taste like?

00:27:00.050 --> 00:27:01.050
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Seaweed.

00:27:01.050 --> 00:27:02.050
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Seaweed?

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:03.050
Yeah.

00:27:03.050 --> 00:27:04.050
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Tasty.

00:27:04.050 --> 00:27:05.050
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Tasty?

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:06.050
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Kombu.

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:07.050
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Kombu.

00:27:07.050 --> 00:27:08.050
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Savory.

00:27:08.050 --> 00:27:09.050
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Savory.

00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:10.050
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Disgusting.

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:11.050
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Disgusting.

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:13.600
[laughs] [laughter] Yeah, it's really odd,
isn't it?

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:15.350
It's very odd.

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:19.570
The reason I do this exercise is that most
of the time when we taste umami, it's in the

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:21.549
presence of a whole lot of other things.

00:27:21.549 --> 00:27:25.230
There's aroma that goes along with it, there's
color, there's texture.

00:27:25.230 --> 00:27:30.560
What this exercise does is really let you
separate salt from umami, which people get

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:32.580
confused about.

00:27:32.580 --> 00:27:35.310
A lot of people will say it tastes like broth.

00:27:35.310 --> 00:27:39.010
It might taste like Dashi or it might taste
like chicken broth.

00:27:39.010 --> 00:27:44.159
What is giving the umami its umami-ness is
free glutamates.

00:27:44.159 --> 00:27:50.190
These are the three forms of glutamates that
we taste: monosodium glutamate, disodium inosinate,

00:27:50.190 --> 00:27:51.850
and disodium guanylate.

00:27:51.850 --> 00:27:53.920
I'm sure that's clear as mud, right?

00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:58.570
Okay, let me explain how umami works.

00:27:58.570 --> 00:28:01.059
These are big protein molecules.

00:28:01.059 --> 00:28:07.289
I use this analogy of someone putting a huge
gumball or a huge cherry tomato in your mouth.

00:28:07.289 --> 00:28:11.610
When it's in that big form, you don't really
get a lot of the flavor from it.

00:28:11.610 --> 00:28:16.530
You have to chew it down to release the flavor
from it.

00:28:16.530 --> 00:28:19.000
That's what happens with umami.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:26.290
Through a number of processes, these big protein
molecules are broken down into smaller free

00:28:26.290 --> 00:28:27.590
glutamates.

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:31.360
These free glutamates are what taste so yummy.

00:28:31.360 --> 00:28:35.270
They are savory, and they're what makes food
taste so good.

00:28:35.270 --> 00:28:37.370
So you take cheese.

00:28:37.370 --> 00:28:40.040
Let's start with a fresh mozzarella.

00:28:40.040 --> 00:28:41.450
Delicious.

00:28:41.450 --> 00:28:47.020
Got a nice fatty mouth feel, it melts, it's
got some dairy notes, perhaps a little buttery,

00:28:47.020 --> 00:28:49.620
but it doesn't have a lot else going on.

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:53.600
You take a cheese, then you age it.

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:59.250
Over the course of aging, those protein molecules
are broken down into these free glutamates.

00:28:59.250 --> 00:29:01.370
Now think about a Parmesan cheese.

00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:03.000
You get the big block of Parmesan.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:04.710
It's crumbly.

00:29:04.710 --> 00:29:08.909
That cheese is loaded with free glutamates.

00:29:08.909 --> 00:29:10.220
That's why it tastes so meaty.

00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:13.789
Sometimes you'll get a good Parmesan or an
aged cheese that has that meaty character

00:29:13.789 --> 00:29:14.940
to it.

00:29:14.940 --> 00:29:16.890
That's umami.

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:19.080
Take a tomato, a green tomato.

00:29:19.080 --> 00:29:20.820
Almost no umami.

00:29:20.820 --> 00:29:28.179
Through the ripening process, it will develop
seven to eight times as much umami.

00:29:28.179 --> 00:29:33.659
These are the things that help develop that
umami: ripening like the tomato, aging like

00:29:33.659 --> 00:29:36.929
the cheese, curing, all those cured meats.

00:29:36.929 --> 00:29:42.790
You take the big protein molecules and through
the curing process, you develop the glutamates.

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:45.330
Drying, fermenting.

00:29:45.330 --> 00:29:48.640
One of the reasons we love fermented food
so much is the development of these glutamates.

00:29:48.640 --> 00:29:49.640
Okay.

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:50.640
So-- yes?

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:51.640
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Evolutionarily, what's the point
of this?

00:29:51.640 --> 00:30:00.530
I'm assuming our ancestors didn't have much
chance to eat those kinds of foods.

00:30:00.530 --> 00:30:01.530
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes, that's a good point.

00:30:01.530 --> 00:30:08.419
There's some debate about whether or not umami
should be considered a basic taste for that

00:30:08.419 --> 00:30:11.279
very reason and the very reason that-- What's
your name?

00:30:11.279 --> 00:30:12.340
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Naha.

00:30:12.340 --> 00:30:18.830
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: --Naha said that it was disgusting
because we generally-- Some of us like it,

00:30:18.830 --> 00:30:19.830
some of us don't like it.

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:24.669
We don't really have a definitive, affective
response to it.

00:30:24.669 --> 00:30:31.840
The protein doesn't necessarily taste like
umami, but the amino acids do.

00:30:31.840 --> 00:30:37.750
Arguably, it was because we need the amino
acids for survival.

00:30:37.750 --> 00:30:38.890
Okay.

00:30:38.890 --> 00:30:42.669
So now we're going to move on to the next
sense, which is smell.

00:30:42.669 --> 00:30:48.440
Everybody take that jelly bean out of your
pocket or your-- What I'm going to ask you

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:52.980
to do is to first of all hold up your right
hand and say, "I promise not to cheat."

00:30:52.980 --> 00:30:54.510
&gt;&gt;all: I promise not to cheat.

00:30:54.510 --> 00:30:55.730
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Okay.

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:56.950
All right.

00:30:56.950 --> 00:30:59.600
We got that on camera.

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:01.529
Grab your nose and just plug it.

00:31:01.529 --> 00:31:04.299
Oh, this is going to difficult right here.

00:31:04.299 --> 00:31:06.110
Here, let me.

00:31:06.110 --> 00:31:07.230
Put it on your lap.

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:09.810
Okay. [laughs] Gotta plug your nose.

00:31:09.810 --> 00:31:13.330
Now the point of this is to disable your sense
of smell.

00:31:13.330 --> 00:31:15.640
Go ahead and put the jelly bean in your mouth.

00:31:15.640 --> 00:31:19.470
I don't want you to release your nose until
I tell you to.

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:24.370
If you're doing this properly, you should
not smell anything.

00:31:24.370 --> 00:31:28.140
So start chewing.

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:29.890
Keep chewing.

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:31.130
Keep chewing.

00:31:31.130 --> 00:31:32.140
Keep chewing.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:33.269
Tell me what you're experiencing.

00:31:33.269 --> 00:31:35.760
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Kinda sweet.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:37.630
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Kinda sweet.

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:38.630
Sweet.

00:31:38.630 --> 00:31:39.630
Yeah.

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:43.330
Kinda sweet, that's kinda-- There's not a
lot of basic taste in a jelly bean.

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:45.010
Release your nose now.

00:31:45.010 --> 00:31:48.390
[pause] Yeah, okay.

00:31:48.390 --> 00:31:49.630
What flavor is it?

00:31:49.630 --> 00:31:51.830
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Melon.

00:31:51.830 --> 00:31:53.299
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Melon?

00:31:53.299 --> 00:31:54.299
Cantaloupe.

00:31:54.299 --> 00:31:55.299
Cantaloupe.

00:31:55.299 --> 00:31:59.270
So what you were getting on your tongue, using
just your sense of taste, was sweet because

00:31:59.270 --> 00:32:03.100
that's the only basic taste that's in jelly
beans.

00:32:03.100 --> 00:32:09.010
Everything else that you smell there, that
whole gestalt of melon, came through your

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:10.300
nose.

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:11.840
That's the aroma.

00:32:11.840 --> 00:32:16.470
It's really important to understand where
the sensory input is coming from.

00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:22.230
That's-- Now hopefully you've got a good appreciation
for how much of the flavor of food comes from

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:23.830
our sense of smell.

00:32:23.830 --> 00:32:33.100
I want to tell you a little bit about a fragrant
flashback, which is my term for how powerful--

00:32:33.100 --> 00:32:35.630
one of the examples of how powerful smell
is.

00:32:35.630 --> 00:32:42.809
This goes back, again, to the lab at Mattson,
where I was walking from my office to taste

00:32:42.809 --> 00:32:46.019
some prototypes.

00:32:46.019 --> 00:32:50.340
I have to step back and go back to something
Scott said, which is that I'm from Baltimore.

00:32:50.340 --> 00:32:54.740
What you should know about Baltimore is that
when I was growing up, in downtown Baltimore,

00:32:54.740 --> 00:33:00.060
the McCormick spice factory was making spices
downtown.

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:04.860
One day, there would be cinnamon in the air
at Baltimore.

00:33:04.860 --> 00:33:08.640
And then they'd switch over the lines and
then they'd have basil.

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:13.169
Later in the day would be cumin, and then
later in the day it'd be coriander.

00:33:13.169 --> 00:33:18.320
So all of these crazy spices were hanging
in the air in downtown Baltimore.

00:33:18.320 --> 00:33:21.179
A random mixture.

00:33:21.179 --> 00:33:25.850
We have the spice library at Mattson with
every spice known to man.

00:33:25.850 --> 00:33:30.419
One of our interns was in there, taking old
spices and dumping them and refilling them

00:33:30.419 --> 00:33:34.320
with fresh spices, because you want to keep
your spices very fresh for the most aroma

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:35.320
impact.

00:33:35.320 --> 00:33:39.090
She takes down the cinnamon, dumps it in the
trash.

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:41.790
Basil, dumps it.

00:33:41.790 --> 00:33:43.140
Coriander, dumps it.

00:33:43.140 --> 00:33:50.549
I'm walking by this trash can and I [laughs]
go over to the trash can and I stick my head

00:33:50.549 --> 00:33:51.660
in it.

00:33:51.660 --> 00:33:55.280
[deep breath in] Home.

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:57.090
[laughs] What?

00:33:57.090 --> 00:34:00.150
So that is the fragrant flashback.

00:34:00.150 --> 00:34:04.460
When you smell something and it transports
you to another time.

00:34:04.460 --> 00:34:09.540
I know you've all had experiences like that,
where you just smell something and you just

00:34:09.540 --> 00:34:12.940
remember something, good or bad.

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:16.820
That is-- There's an anatomical reason for
this.

00:34:16.820 --> 00:34:26.329
When any of our senses are detected through
our neurons, through our receptors, the information

00:34:26.329 --> 00:34:28.839
goes on its way up to our brain.

00:34:28.839 --> 00:34:33.099
It goes through something called the thalamus,
and then it goes on to the brain, and we smell,

00:34:33.099 --> 00:34:35.040
or sight, or whatever.

00:34:35.040 --> 00:34:37.270
I'm sorry, taste or sight.

00:34:37.270 --> 00:34:40.780
Smell does not go through the thalamus.

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:49.280
When you smell something, it goes right to
your brain without making this stop in the

00:34:49.280 --> 00:34:50.540
thalamus.

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:56.339
It's a more direct route from sensory experience
to your brain.

00:34:56.339 --> 00:35:02.710
We think that is because smell is our most
primitive sense.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:07.610
But that's also why we have such a direct
connection to emotion when we smell things.

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:11.500
There's two different ways that we smell.

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:16.329
The first way is when we just take something
and we sniff it.

00:35:16.329 --> 00:35:18.010
Stick your nose in something and smell it.

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:20.820
That's called orthonasal olfaction.

00:35:20.820 --> 00:35:24.190
That's when the smell molecules are going
like this.

00:35:24.190 --> 00:35:29.040
The other way we smell something is called
retronasal olfaction.

00:35:29.040 --> 00:35:31.280
That's when the smell comes from your mouth.

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:36.490
You put a food in your mouth, you've chewed
the food, and the volatile aromas that are

00:35:36.490 --> 00:35:42.050
released from it are sucked up and through
the back of your nasal passages.

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:48.540
They come back past your olfactory receptors
this way.

00:35:48.540 --> 00:35:55.740
The quality of those smells this way [sniffs]
and chew chew that way is a little bit different.

00:35:55.740 --> 00:36:04.270
We're going to do an exercise now where everybody
take your straw and bend it like this.

00:36:04.270 --> 00:36:05.890
Take the long end and put it in your mouth.

00:36:05.890 --> 00:36:09.630
See how well they follow the directions.

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:10.900
Okay.

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:12.950
Don't do this yet, but let me show you what
you're going to do.

00:36:12.950 --> 00:36:17.740
So I've got something in this cup that is
very aromatic.

00:36:17.740 --> 00:36:22.000
The volatile aromas have been building up
in the headspace.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:24.170
There's a little hole here.

00:36:24.170 --> 00:36:29.170
Without looking at it, just take that button,
push it to the side, and stick the short end

00:36:29.170 --> 00:36:30.770
of your straw in the hole.

00:36:30.770 --> 00:36:33.660
So you're going like this.

00:36:33.660 --> 00:36:36.920
Start breathing in and out.

00:36:36.920 --> 00:36:44.340
[breathing noises] Just breathe normally.

00:36:44.340 --> 00:36:45.340
You smell it?

00:36:45.340 --> 00:36:46.340
Don't tell me yet.

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:47.340
You smell it?

00:36:47.340 --> 00:36:48.990
You all smell it?

00:36:48.990 --> 00:36:49.990
What is it?

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:52.030
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Blue cheese.

00:36:52.030 --> 00:36:53.810
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Blue cheese.

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:54.810
You got it.

00:36:54.810 --> 00:36:55.810
Okay.

00:36:55.810 --> 00:36:59.540
They did not smell it before it got into their
mouth and went up that way.

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:02.020
That was all retronasal olfaction.

00:37:02.020 --> 00:37:05.670
Go ahead and take the lid off and stick your
nose in.

00:37:05.670 --> 00:37:11.480
[pause] A little different, huh?

00:37:11.480 --> 00:37:12.650
Different.

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:16.589
&gt;&gt;Male #1: It's more strong.

00:37:16.589 --> 00:37:21.020
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: It's more strong, for sure, because
you're sticking your nose in there.

00:37:21.020 --> 00:37:26.400
The way that we experience these volatile
aromas is slightly different given how they

00:37:26.400 --> 00:37:30.339
go in, whether we detect them this way or
that way.

00:37:30.339 --> 00:37:35.710
We don't really know why that is, but we know
it happens.

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:40.561
This could also explain why something like
a stinky cheese, a really stinky cheese, may

00:37:40.561 --> 00:37:41.930
just smell wrong.

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:43.480
It just smells gross.

00:37:43.480 --> 00:37:49.070
Then you put it in your mouth and you chew
it, and it's really pleasant because there's

00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:50.089
something different happening.

00:37:50.089 --> 00:37:53.220
Now, of course, when you put something in
your mouth and you chew it, you're also using

00:37:53.220 --> 00:37:58.440
your sense of taste, and you're probably getting
some saltiness and some sour and maybe a little

00:37:58.440 --> 00:37:59.570
bitter.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:01.849
But you're also getting the mouth feel of
the cheese.

00:38:01.849 --> 00:38:03.070
It just coats your tongue.

00:38:03.070 --> 00:38:06.810
It's got a nice fatty mouth feel.

00:38:06.810 --> 00:38:12.980
So that's smell.

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:18.119
The way that I describe it in the book is
the difference between taste and smell.

00:38:18.119 --> 00:38:21.200
It's like a piece of art, because food is
art.

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:26.050
If it's really well made, you have a beautiful
piece of art in front of you three times a

00:38:26.050 --> 00:38:27.610
day.

00:38:27.610 --> 00:38:32.570
Taste, those five basic tastes, are like the
outlines of the drawing.

00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:35.810
They set up the structure of the food.

00:38:35.810 --> 00:38:40.200
But if all you had was the basic tastes, like
that jelly bean exercise, all you'd have is

00:38:40.200 --> 00:38:42.340
sweet a lot of the time.

00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:44.370
All you'd have is sour some of the time.

00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:46.380
It's not really that interesting.

00:38:46.380 --> 00:38:53.880
But when you add smell, the smell comes and
fills in the details.

00:38:53.880 --> 00:39:00.190
And so this art, this beautiful work of art,
becomes what you know it to be, the signature

00:39:00.190 --> 00:39:01.650
work of art.

00:39:01.650 --> 00:39:08.850
&gt;&gt;Female #1: I have a quick question.

00:39:08.850 --> 00:39:10.884
When you have a cold, is it only blocking
that side but it's not blocking the other

00:39:10.884 --> 00:39:11.884
side?

00:39:11.884 --> 00:39:14.730
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: It's usually blocking both ways
because the mucus in your nose, it's in your

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:15.730
nasal passage.

00:39:15.730 --> 00:39:18.910
It doesn't matter which way it's going by,
there's too much mucus for you to be able

00:39:18.910 --> 00:39:19.910
to smell it.

00:39:19.910 --> 00:39:21.869
It's in the way of the olfactory receptors.

00:39:21.869 --> 00:39:26.930
But that's a good question.

00:39:26.930 --> 00:39:31.650
With smell, it fills in the details for us.

00:39:31.650 --> 00:39:33.970
It gives us the pleasure from food.

00:39:33.970 --> 00:39:39.869
Remember, taste is the deciding sense, smell
is the pleasure that we get from food.

00:39:39.869 --> 00:39:44.970
Now I'm going to talk about touch and texture.

00:39:44.970 --> 00:39:52.310
I'm going to talk about texture in combination
with what you just learned about smell.

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:54.510
You guys have a-- hopefully you have a spoon.

00:39:54.510 --> 00:39:55.770
Do you have a spoon on your plate?

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:56.770
&gt;&gt;Male #1: No.

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:57.770
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: No.

00:39:57.770 --> 00:40:00.130
Why don't you take this straw and just dip
it in the butter.

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:03.490
What-- oh, there you go.

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:10.700
What everybody has here is-- Just dip the
spoon in and don't eat it yet.

00:40:10.700 --> 00:40:15.060
[scraping sound] What they've got is unsalted
butter.

00:40:15.060 --> 00:40:19.640
When we're cooking, when we're developing
foods at Mattson, we always use unsalted butter.

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:23.740
If you use salted butter when you take the
amount of butter up in your recipe, you also

00:40:23.740 --> 00:40:25.060
take the amount of salt up.

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:29.940
You want to separate those variables so you
can change the variables separately.

00:40:29.940 --> 00:40:32.020
This is unsalted butter.

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:37.079
Now take the spoon in one hand and close your
nose with your other hand.

00:40:37.079 --> 00:40:41.830
What I'm going to prove to them is butter
has no flavor.

00:40:41.830 --> 00:40:45.210
I'm sorry, butter has no taste.

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:50.300
Plug your nose, put the butter in your mouth,
and just swish it around.

00:40:50.300 --> 00:40:55.890
[pause] What are you tasting?

00:40:55.890 --> 00:40:56.890
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Oil.

00:40:56.890 --> 00:40:57.890
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Oil.

00:40:57.890 --> 00:40:58.890
Nothing.

00:40:58.890 --> 00:40:59.890
Nothing.

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:01.140
Okay, let your nose go.

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:05.530
Butter, unsalted butter, has zero taste.

00:41:05.530 --> 00:41:11.480
There's no sweet, no sour, no bitter, no salt,
no umami.

00:41:11.480 --> 00:41:17.170
I always thought of butter as being creamy
and sweet and-- yeah, it's creamy, but it's

00:41:17.170 --> 00:41:18.170
not sweet.

00:41:18.170 --> 00:41:20.520
It doesn't have any sweetness in it.

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:23.420
What we love about butter is not the taste
of butter.

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:26.490
You don't like the taste of butter because
it has no taste.

00:41:26.490 --> 00:41:33.600
What you like about butter is that oily mouth
feel in combination with those lovely, buttery,

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:36.250
floral, green aromas that you get.

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:39.260
Go home and do that tonight with unsalted
butter.

00:41:39.260 --> 00:41:41.829
This was such an "Aha!" for me.

00:41:41.829 --> 00:41:43.890
Butter has no taste?!

00:41:43.890 --> 00:41:45.280
It's crazy.

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:47.350
But we do love the flavor of butter.

00:41:47.350 --> 00:41:51.700
&gt;&gt;Male #7: When you brown butter, are you
developing the aromatics or the umami of it?

00:41:51.700 --> 00:41:57.440
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes, but that butter also, if you're
using unsalted, will not have any taste either.

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:58.440
No.

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:03.220
You are developing the aroma compounds through
the browning process, but if you hold your

00:42:03.220 --> 00:42:04.220
nose, same thing.

00:42:04.220 --> 00:42:08.000
You're going to get no taste, no taste, no
taste, fatty mouth feel butter.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.390
All right.

00:42:10.390 --> 00:42:16.730
Now we're going to talk about kinesthesia,
which is the awareness of the position and

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:22.180
movement of the parts of the body by means
of sensory organs and the muscles and joints.

00:42:22.180 --> 00:42:29.510
This is where texture and touch gets really
interesting because we put food in our mouth

00:42:29.510 --> 00:42:30.599
all the time.

00:42:30.599 --> 00:42:35.420
We talk while we're chewing and swallowing
without even thinking about it.

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:40.540
It's a pretty amazing thing that we do [laughs]
if you think about it.

00:42:40.540 --> 00:42:45.640
We can manage the swallowing, the chewing,
and the breathing at the same time.

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:47.819
How do we know when it's time to swallow?

00:42:47.819 --> 00:42:49.230
We just know.

00:42:49.230 --> 00:42:55.010
We're aware of the food in our mouth at all
times, but we're not paying attention to it.

00:42:55.010 --> 00:42:56.150
But we're aware of it.

00:42:56.150 --> 00:42:58.880
That's why we don't choke ourselves to death
when we eat.

00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:02.970
We know when it's time to swallow.

00:43:02.970 --> 00:43:08.180
If you think about it, next time you chew,
think about what side you're chewing on.

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:13.319
Everybody always has a dominant side, but
you only chew on one side at a time, never

00:43:13.319 --> 00:43:16.400
chew on both sides at the same time.

00:43:16.400 --> 00:43:17.400
Doesn't happen.

00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:20.691
You chew over here, then you push it over
there, then you chew over there, then you

00:43:20.691 --> 00:43:23.869
push it over there, then you chew, then you
push it over.

00:43:23.869 --> 00:43:25.520
Can't chew on both sides.

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:30.240
It's the only joint in the human body that
you can't operate separately.

00:43:30.240 --> 00:43:32.530
You can't do it.

00:43:32.530 --> 00:43:37.740
Another experiment for you to do.

00:43:37.740 --> 00:43:43.160
There are a couple of foods that I called
irri-tastes because we commonly think of them

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:45.050
as tastes, but they're not tastes at all.

00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:50.839
They are actually tactile experiences, and
they are irritants.

00:43:50.839 --> 00:43:53.130
The first one is tannin.

00:43:53.130 --> 00:43:57.770
If you think of the tannin that you get when
you drink tea that's not sweetened.

00:43:57.770 --> 00:44:03.500
Or red wine, a really big California Cabernet,
has tons of tannin.

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:05.750
That tannin will feel astringent on your tongue.

00:44:05.750 --> 00:44:07.300
It will dry your tongue out.

00:44:07.300 --> 00:44:09.099
It will suck all the moisture out of your
tongue.

00:44:09.099 --> 00:44:10.579
That is a textural experience.

00:44:10.579 --> 00:44:12.819
That's a tactile experience, not a taste.

00:44:12.819 --> 00:44:13.980
It's not bitter.

00:44:13.980 --> 00:44:19.280
Now if it's grapes, there might be some bitterness
in there, but the tannic quality of grapes

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:24.560
and tea is not a bitterness, it's an astringent
texture.

00:44:24.560 --> 00:44:26.320
JalapeÃ±os.

