00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:35.560
So you're constantly making these judgments
about food based on its sight.

00:46:35.560 --> 00:46:40.390
Sometimes, once you see it and you make a
judgment, it's really hard to change your

00:46:40.390 --> 00:46:44.700
mind once something's not quite right.

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:45.810
Beer brewers.

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:49.060
They were brought into a research facility.

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:50.359
There were three beers.

00:46:50.359 --> 00:46:53.930
Let's just say one was Amstel, one was Budweiser,
and one was Coors.

00:46:53.930 --> 00:47:00.349
A, B, and C. They took three glasses of Amstel
beer, poured them into pints, and then they

00:47:00.349 --> 00:47:04.880
added a little bit of color to number 2 and
3 Amstel.

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:08.180
They did the same thing for Bud and Coors.

00:47:08.180 --> 00:47:13.630
So you've got three glasses of Amstel in three
different colors, three Bud, three Coors,

00:47:13.630 --> 00:47:14.850
three different colors.

00:47:14.850 --> 00:47:21.550
Then you have these professional beer brewers
come in and taste them in the dark.

00:47:21.550 --> 00:47:29.589
When they're sitting in a dark room and they
have to rely only on their senses excluding

00:47:29.589 --> 00:47:31.670
sight, they get them right.

00:47:31.670 --> 00:47:34.620
They're beer brewers, they should know how
to taste beer.

00:47:34.620 --> 00:47:35.920
Then you turn the lights on.

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:38.780
You have them do the same exact exercise.

00:47:38.780 --> 00:47:39.780
And they fail miserably.

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:44.500
These are professional beer brewers that do
this.

00:47:44.500 --> 00:47:46.301
What do they do?

00:47:46.301 --> 00:47:48.109
They group them by color.

00:47:48.109 --> 00:47:50.210
Then you ask them, "Why did you group them
this way?"

00:47:50.210 --> 00:47:52.160
"Oh, well they all taste the same.

00:47:52.160 --> 00:47:53.160
These all taste the same."

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:56.740
Well, they just did the experiment and got
it right in the dark.

00:47:56.740 --> 00:48:01.150
We don't even know when our eyes have overrided
what we experience.

00:48:01.150 --> 00:48:02.589
It happens all the time.

00:48:02.589 --> 00:48:07.470
This type of research was done with gelatin,
it was done with candies, it was done with

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:09.089
fruity beverages.

00:48:09.089 --> 00:48:11.240
You can do it with wine.

00:48:11.240 --> 00:48:15.829
There's a very popular, a very famous study
that was done with white wine with a little

00:48:15.829 --> 00:48:19.240
bit of red added to one of them so it looked
like red wine.

00:48:19.240 --> 00:48:20.240
Same thing.

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:21.240
You can fool wine professionals.

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:23.450
[audience member coughs]
Why?

00:48:23.450 --> 00:48:27.500
Why does our eyes, why are they so influential?

00:48:27.500 --> 00:48:28.500
There's a couple reasons.

00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:34.710
The first is that sight is fast in terms of
processing the sensory input.

00:48:34.710 --> 00:48:37.680
Sight happens ten times faster than smell.

00:48:37.680 --> 00:48:41.240
If we were able to control it in a perfect
environment, which would be really hard to

00:48:41.240 --> 00:48:48.130
do, but if we could control when we smelled
something and when we saw it, we would process

00:48:48.130 --> 00:48:49.500
the smell faster.

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:53.750
I'm sorry, we would process the sight faster.

00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:55.109
It's faster than the other senses.

00:48:55.109 --> 00:48:57.840
The other thing is that sight happens at a
distance.

00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:00.470
Back there, you can probably see me, right?

00:49:00.470 --> 00:49:04.210
I hope you can't smell me.

00:49:04.210 --> 00:49:06.200
You have to be a lot closer to smell something.

00:49:06.200 --> 00:49:10.780
You have to be even closer still to taste
it, remember, because taste is a contact sense.

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:13.150
It has to be in touch with your tongue.

00:49:13.150 --> 00:49:18.330
So you have these senses that have to be a
whole lot closer to you for you to start making

00:49:18.330 --> 00:49:19.700
judgments about it.

00:49:19.700 --> 00:49:25.140
The first one that happens, the first thing
you see, biases or infects your ability to

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:27.780
make a good decision.

