00:53:30.900 --> 00:53:38.020
In summary, [pause] what I have hopefully
taught you today is just the basic fundamentals.

00:53:38.020 --> 00:53:41.420
I have a chapter on each one of the five basic
senses.

00:53:41.420 --> 00:53:45.460
All five of which we use incredibly well when
we experience food.

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:54.770
Food that tastes good, using the word improperly,
looks good, sounds good, feels good, smells

00:53:54.770 --> 00:53:58.530
good, and tastes good.

00:53:58.530 --> 00:54:02.980
Then I have a chapter on each one of the five
basic tastes and go into them in great detail:

00:54:02.980 --> 00:54:06.080
sweet, sour, bitter, salt, and umami.

00:54:06.080 --> 00:54:12.890
And how understanding how they work and how
they work in balance and how you can balance

00:54:12.890 --> 00:54:17.870
the tastes in a food is really important,
because once you get the five basic tastes

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:20.960
right in a dish, the rest is easy.

00:54:20.960 --> 00:54:24.550
It's the structure of the dish.

00:54:24.550 --> 00:54:33.210
I say once you have this fundamental understanding
of how we experience taste, just like anything

00:54:33.210 --> 00:54:38.680
that you study, the more you understand about
it, the more appreciation you're going to

00:54:38.680 --> 00:54:39.680
have for it.

00:54:39.680 --> 00:54:44.690
The more you study something, the more you
understand, the more pleasure you get from

00:54:44.690 --> 00:54:45.690
it.

00:54:45.690 --> 00:54:50.950
That is the whole point of this book, is that
you start to understand what's happening via

00:54:50.950 --> 00:54:55.640
all of your senses and all of your tastes
and how they're being stimulated.

00:54:55.640 --> 00:55:00.369
Then you can take more pleasure from it.

