Once you do that exercise, then you're going
to be much more aware of the umami in your

00:56:25.579 --> 00:56:27.240
foods.

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:29.780
It's simple training.

00:56:29.780 --> 00:56:34.631
One of the hardest things to do is to take
something and just sniff it and know what

00:56:34.631 --> 00:56:36.710
it is without seeing it.

00:56:36.710 --> 00:56:39.070
That is really hard for chefs to do.

00:56:39.070 --> 00:56:40.650
It's just very, very hard.

00:56:40.650 --> 00:56:46.470
But people that do it professionally, people
that are in the wine business, for example,

00:56:46.470 --> 00:56:50.890
or in the perfuming business, tend to be better
at it.

00:56:50.890 --> 00:56:53.770
It does show that practice makes perfect.

00:56:53.770 --> 00:56:58.500
For example, when I started in food development,
my colleagues would talk about rancidity and

00:56:58.500 --> 00:56:59.940
what was rancid.

00:56:59.940 --> 00:57:05.420
I had no idea what rancid was, so I begged
them, "Please let me taste something rancid.

00:57:05.420 --> 00:57:09.350
[laughter] Next time there's something rancid,
can you point it out to me?"

00:57:09.350 --> 00:57:12.880
I have a little rancid vial, if anybody wants
to smell rancidity.

00:57:12.880 --> 00:57:17.510
Because I had to train myself because I wasn't
detecting it.

00:57:17.510 --> 00:57:19.790
I didn't know what to look for, what to smell
for.

00:57:19.790 --> 00:57:25.920
Now I know, and now-- Olive oil, I can smell
rancid olive oil a mile away.

00:57:25.920 --> 00:57:28.410
But 20 years ago, I couldn't.

00:57:28.410 --> 00:57:29.950
It's practice makes perfect.

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:32.710
Really, really, really does help.

00:57:32.710 --> 00:57:38.521
&gt;&gt;Male #8: Does the practice makes perfect
principle hold true for foods you don't like?

00:57:38.521 --> 00:57:40.020
Like Brussels sprouts?

00:57:40.020 --> 00:57:41.020
[laughs]

00:57:41.020 --> 00:57:42.020
