00:57:42.020 --> 00:57:44.040
Yes, yes, yes.

00:57:44.040 --> 00:57:53.410
Research has shown that it takes between five
and eight attempts at a food before not rejecting

00:57:53.410 --> 00:57:54.410
it.

00:57:54.410 --> 00:57:56.720
That doesn't mean you're going to become,
after the fifth or the eighth taste, you're

00:57:56.720 --> 00:58:01.839
going to become the world's biggest fan of
Brussels sprouts, but keep trying it.

00:58:01.839 --> 00:58:05.000
Give yourself a couple of times.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:10.750
Your taste buds and your olfactory system
change dramatically as you age, so you might

00:58:10.750 --> 00:58:16.250
decide, if you keep trying it, keep trying
it every couple of months or every season,

00:58:16.250 --> 00:58:18.400
every Brussels sprout season, try it again.

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:24.460
As you age and your olfactory changes, you
may be able to experience it with less of

00:58:24.460 --> 00:58:32.570
the sulfury smell or you may be able to experience
it with more sour and less of the bitter.

00:58:32.570 --> 00:58:35.800
Your whole physiology with regard to taste
changes.

00:58:35.800 --> 00:58:38.380
So I would suggest continuing to taste.

00:58:38.380 --> 00:58:41.250
&gt;&gt;Male #8: So there are two pieces to it?

00:58:41.250 --> 00:58:44.609
There's the degree which I can affect it by
consuming it formally--

00:58:44.609 --> 00:58:45.609
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes.

00:58:45.609 --> 00:58:46.609
It's called mere-exposure.

00:58:46.609 --> 00:58:48.339
It's just the mere exposure to something.

00:58:48.339 --> 00:58:49.680
I'll give you an example.

00:58:49.680 --> 00:58:56.390
When I started in the Mattson lab 15 plus
years ago, I hated canned tuna.

00:58:56.390 --> 00:58:58.810
Just the smell of canned tuna was disgusting
to me.

00:58:58.810 --> 00:59:01.829
Then I get a tuna project.

00:59:01.829 --> 00:59:04.040
For four years, I ate tuna every day.

00:59:04.040 --> 00:59:05.440
I had to.

00:59:05.440 --> 00:59:07.160
I tasted canned tuna every day.

00:59:07.160 --> 00:59:09.090
I love tuna today.

00:59:09.090 --> 00:59:11.000
I love it!

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:13.000
Because I can-- I don't like every kind of
tuna.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:14.500
I like good tuna.

00:59:14.500 --> 00:59:16.609
And I'm discriminating now about my canned
tuna.

00:59:16.609 --> 00:59:19.670
I like the once cooked and not the twice cooked,
and I like the albacore and I don't like the

00:59:19.670 --> 00:59:20.670
light.

00:59:20.670 --> 00:59:22.370
So mere-exposure will help.

00:59:22.370 --> 00:59:23.370
&gt;&gt;Male #8: Okay, great.

00:59:23.370 --> 00:59:24.370
Thank you.

00:59:24.370 --> 00:59:26.760
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Have you tried a stinky tofu
or durian?

00:59:26.760 --> 00:59:28.460
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes.

00:59:28.460 --> 00:59:32.530
I think-- the question was: have I tried stinky
tofu or durian?

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:37.390
I think durian is, I think there's something
similar that happens with durian that happens

00:59:37.390 --> 00:59:43.810
with a stinky cheese, which is the orthonasal
smell of durian is just-- If you haven't smelled

00:59:43.810 --> 00:59:50.329
it, it's kinda like rotting flesh, like garbage,
sewage.

00:59:50.329 --> 00:59:52.579
It's just really rank.

00:59:52.579 --> 00:59:54.450
But people love it.

00:59:54.450 --> 00:59:56.990
So something different happens when you eat
it.

00:59:56.990 --> 01:00:02.260
Of course, when you eat it, now you're not
just getting-- What happens, I think, is when

01:00:02.260 --> 01:00:07.460
you're smelling it, all you're getting are
those rank odors, and you get them one way.

01:00:07.460 --> 01:00:08.690
Then you put the fruit in your mouth.

01:00:08.690 --> 01:00:14.049
Now you've got sweet and sour basic tastes,
because now you can use your sense of taste.

01:00:14.049 --> 01:00:19.390
So you take that rank odor and you combine
it with the sweet and the sour that you get

01:00:19.390 --> 01:00:22.730
from taste, and now it's something different
altogether.

01:00:22.730 --> 01:00:26.420
Maybe things start to fall in place.

01:00:26.420 --> 01:00:30.780
There are a lot of foods like that, where
we think that the smell is just so-- Stinky

01:00:30.780 --> 01:00:32.960
tofu comes up all the time.

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:34.230
Just unbearable.

01:00:34.230 --> 01:00:35.230
But taste it.

01:00:35.230 --> 01:00:39.000
If you put it in your mouth, if you can get
it into your mouth, you will have a different

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:40.359
experience of it.

01:00:40.359 --> 01:00:43.130
Of course, a lot of this is cultural, too.

01:00:43.130 --> 01:00:44.130
Stinky cheese is.

01:00:44.130 --> 01:00:48.510
You grow up in France, and a stinky cheese
shop smells really good to you.

01:00:48.510 --> 01:00:49.510
[pause]

01:00:49.510 --> 01:00:57.470
&gt;&gt;Male #9: So my daughter says that kale is
the most hideous thing ever.

01:00:57.470 --> 01:00:58.470
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Kale?

01:00:58.470 --> 01:00:59.470
&gt;&gt;Male #9: Kale.

01:00:59.470 --> 01:01:01.059
And my wife is convinced that is has no taste
at all.

01:01:01.059 --> 01:01:03.109
You can't even tell it's there.

01:01:03.109 --> 01:01:06.260
How can I let them know that they're both
right?

01:01:06.260 --> 01:01:08.920
That they both have different taste experiences?

01:01:08.920 --> 01:01:13.770
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: What you've just described is what
I hope people take away from this book, which

01:01:13.770 --> 01:01:16.180
is taste empathy.

01:01:16.180 --> 01:01:18.890
[laughter] We have to have taste empathy.

01:01:18.890 --> 01:01:21.180
Really, we don't talk about it in this country.

01:01:21.180 --> 01:01:26.099
Like it's okay for us to say, "I can't see
that over there because I don't really have

01:01:26.099 --> 01:01:33.569
good eyesight" but yet we don't accept the
fact that one of our other senses can vary

01:01:33.569 --> 01:01:35.670
from person to person.

01:01:35.670 --> 01:01:36.670
Right?

01:01:36.670 --> 01:01:40.299
We all have different vision, different visual
acuity.

01:01:40.299 --> 01:01:45.290
What I think happens, or is happening in your
household, is your wife is a tolerant taster,

01:01:45.290 --> 01:01:54.829
meaning she has probably a very not so densely
populated tongue, with taste buds, and she

01:01:54.829 --> 01:01:59.410
genetically is probably also unable to taste
the bitterness in kale.

01:01:59.410 --> 01:02:01.490
She might be right.

01:02:01.490 --> 01:02:10.030
To her, in her private sensory world, kale
is crunchy and fresh and vegetal and not bitter.

01:02:10.030 --> 01:02:14.480
Then in your daughter's sensory world, it
might be the most bitter thing she's every

01:02:14.480 --> 01:02:15.520
put in her mouth.

01:02:15.520 --> 01:02:16.800
And they're both right.

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:17.800
You're exactly right.

01:02:17.800 --> 01:02:18.800
They're both right.

01:02:18.800 --> 01:02:24.869
Of course you can never know what-- another
person's sensory experience.

01:02:24.869 --> 01:02:26.130
You should do that at home.

01:02:26.130 --> 01:02:31.760
Take the blue dye and paint your daughter's
and your wife's tongue and then have them

01:02:31.760 --> 01:02:36.039
count the taste buds inside the hole of the
reinforcement.

01:02:36.039 --> 01:02:41.339
They can prove it to themselves that they
have very different anatomy.

01:02:41.339 --> 01:02:44.510
That hopefully will give your wife some taste
empathy.

01:02:44.510 --> 01:02:47.430
&gt;&gt;Male #10: Is it big enough to count?

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:49.070
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Yes.

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:52.500
You're just going to need to get really close
to a mirror.

01:02:52.500 --> 01:02:56.660
But watch out, because blue dye stains carpets
and towels.

01:02:56.660 --> 01:02:58.500
I found this out the hard way.

01:02:58.500 --> 01:02:59.500
[laughs]

01:02:59.500 --> 01:03:08.650
&gt;&gt;Male #11: Along those lines, I was wondering
if you have any explanation, specifically

01:03:08.650 --> 01:03:12.079
for why some people claim that cilantro tastes
like soap?

01:03:12.079 --> 01:03:15.130
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: I always get this question.

01:03:15.130 --> 01:03:16.630
Always get this question.

01:03:16.630 --> 01:03:18.720
Cilantro is a really interesting thing.

01:03:18.720 --> 01:03:21.040
In the food world, we call it polarizing.

01:03:21.040 --> 01:03:23.380
You just don't sit on the fence about cilantro.

01:03:23.380 --> 01:03:26.030
You either love it or you hate it.

01:03:26.030 --> 01:03:28.910
[laughter] We know a lot about cilantro.

01:03:28.910 --> 01:03:33.880
We know that there is a genetic component
to your liking of cilantro.

01:03:33.880 --> 01:03:38.670
The way we know this is that we do research
with twins.

01:03:38.670 --> 01:03:41.500
There's this place in Ohio called Twinsburg.

01:03:41.500 --> 01:03:42.890
Every year, they have a twin festival.

01:03:42.890 --> 01:03:44.990
All these twins go there.

01:03:44.990 --> 01:03:50.970
The researchers are just drooling at the mouth,
because they can take a set of fraternal twins

01:03:50.970 --> 01:03:54.680
and a set of identical twins and test something.

01:03:54.680 --> 01:03:59.910
Of course, you can determine, by the correlation,
whether or not there's a genetic component

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:00.910
to it.

01:04:00.910 --> 01:04:06.109
If the correlation is perfect for the identical
twins who share 100% of their DNA but not

01:04:06.109 --> 01:04:11.650
for the fraternal twins, who don't, in fact,
they're just like any other set of siblings,

01:04:11.650 --> 01:04:13.640
you know there's a genetic component to it.

01:04:13.640 --> 01:04:16.799
We know there's a genetic component to the
liking of cilantro.

01:04:16.799 --> 01:04:21.660
The other thing that we know about cilantro--
There's been a lot of research on this subject.

01:04:21.660 --> 01:04:25.140
This is such a polarizing food.

01:04:25.140 --> 01:04:35.250
What apparently happens is that when you run
cilantro through the GCMS, the gas chromatograph

01:04:35.250 --> 01:04:40.690
mass spectrometer, which is what you can run
something through to get the volatile aroma

01:04:40.690 --> 01:04:44.340
menu out of it.

01:04:44.340 --> 01:04:50.890
You expose someone to the smells that occur
in cilantro.

01:04:50.890 --> 01:05:02.119
There is an aroma experience that people who
love cilantro get, that people who don't,

01:05:02.119 --> 01:05:03.119
don't get.

01:05:03.119 --> 01:05:04.119
The same thing.

01:05:04.119 --> 01:05:12.760
People who hate it, they're smelling different--
When you run something through this GCMS,

01:05:12.760 --> 01:05:16.349
it gives you spikes in volatile aromas.

01:05:16.349 --> 01:05:22.819
There are certain things, certain volatiles
in the cilantro, that people that hate it

01:05:22.819 --> 01:05:25.470
are not experiencing.

01:05:25.470 --> 01:05:29.010
There are certain things in there that people
who love it are not experiencing.

01:05:29.010 --> 01:05:32.920
So they're getting different pictures of it.

01:05:32.920 --> 01:05:37.309
They're not-- Neither one of them is getting
the same picture as the other.

01:05:37.309 --> 01:05:38.490
This is true of cilantro.

01:05:38.490 --> 01:05:40.359
It's probably true of a lot of foods.

01:05:40.359 --> 01:05:45.299
But there's been a lot of research done on
cilantro.

01:05:45.299 --> 01:05:52.530
That is that your personal experience of the
aroma of cilantro may be very different than

01:05:52.530 --> 01:05:53.760
someone else's.

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:59.310
The beautiful stuff that makes it beautiful
to you may not occur, may not be happening,

01:05:59.310 --> 01:06:01.240
in someone else's experience.

01:06:01.240 --> 01:06:07.069
Or the disgusting part that you find really
offensive may not be experienced by people

01:06:07.069 --> 01:06:08.069
who at it.

01:06:08.069 --> 01:06:13.030
&gt;&gt;Female #3: Going back to your early comment
about sound in restaurants, does that mean

01:06:13.030 --> 01:06:20.700
that if you're a really good chef, you should
try to get a really, really quiet restaurant,

01:06:20.700 --> 01:06:24.530
and if your food's not so good, you should
have it as loud as you want, blare loud music,

01:06:24.530 --> 01:06:25.530
and everything?

01:06:25.530 --> 01:06:26.530
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: I don't think it's that literal.

01:06:26.530 --> 01:06:27.530
I hope chefs don't take it as that literal.

01:06:27.530 --> 01:06:29.630
Of course you want appropriate sound in your
restaurant.

01:06:29.630 --> 01:06:35.070
You want to pair the sound and the music with
the food.

01:06:35.070 --> 01:06:37.880
It needs to be appropriate.

01:06:37.880 --> 01:06:43.470
I think what chefs try to do, or what restauranteurs,
I don't know that it's chefs necessarily,

01:06:43.470 --> 01:06:46.860
what restauranteurs try to do is build ambiance
into the restaurant.

01:06:46.860 --> 01:06:52.069
They try to build energy into the restaurant
via sound.

01:06:52.069 --> 01:06:56.910
That can work in some cases where the food
can stand up to it and where you want that

01:06:56.910 --> 01:06:58.730
energy.

01:06:58.730 --> 01:07:03.840
There are other restaurants where the food
is much more subtle, and you want people to

01:07:03.840 --> 01:07:08.570
experience the subtlety of it, which probably
wouldn't work.

01:07:08.570 --> 01:07:14.700
It's so different for every experience, every
restaurant, every chef, every owner, and every

01:07:14.700 --> 01:07:16.059
type of food.

01:07:16.059 --> 01:07:20.070
It's just-- What I'd like people to think
about is just think about it, period.

01:07:20.070 --> 01:07:24.120
Just think about the sound of food, which
we just don't think about those two things

01:07:24.120 --> 01:07:25.120
together.

01:07:25.120 --> 01:07:28.640
&gt;&gt;Giambastiani: All right, well, I think that
wraps up our time for right now.

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:30.960
We'll have some time for more questions at
the book signing.

01:07:30.960 --> 01:07:32.190
But Barb, thank you very much for speaking
with us today.

01:07:32.190 --> 01:07:33.190
&gt;&gt;Stuckey: Thank you.

01:07:33.190 --> 01:07:34.190
Thank you guys for having me.

